  </relevant-files>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Verify task 086 passed: read `projects/sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair/ledgers/exit-ledger.md` and confirm "Final Verification Complete" section is present with all 4 verifications ✅ PASS. If absent or any FAIL, HALT.</step>
    <step order="2">Read `exit-ledger.md` in full to extract closure data for the lessons-learned doc: per-§6.2-state counts, per-tier disposition, sibling-coordination outcomes, actual vs estimated effort.</step>
    <step order="3">Write `projects/sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair/notes/lessons-learned.md` (NEW file) with these sections:
      (a) **Header**: project name, closure date, total person-hours actual vs design.md §10 estimate (80-124h), wall-clock actual vs estimate (16-27 days).
      (b) **What went well**: e.g., parallelism executed as designed; triple-run gate caught X flaky tests; sibling-coordination model avoided merge conflicts; etc.
      (c) **What was harder than expected**: e.g., specific cluster surprises; researcher verdict requiring helper fallback; particular test files needing more time than estimated.
      (d) **Escalations summary**: count of §4.8 rewrite escalations; outcome (approved / denied / re-routed); list of files with rewrite-request links.
      (e) **Sibling-coordination outcomes**: per design.md §2.3 (Action Engine, Insights Phase 2, Communications) — what happened; what follow-up commitments persist post-close.
      (f) **Recommendations for follow-on Projects 2-5** (per design.md §11.1):
         - Project 2 (test architecture split): what THIS project learned about factory coupling, in-process HTTP via `WebApplicationFactory`, and which cluster patterns suggest the architecture split is now-urgent vs can-wait.
         - Project 3 (coverage): which areas have weak coverage that should be Project 3's first targets.
         - Project 4 (test quality): which mocked-orchestration tests are low-value candidates for rewrite.
         - Project 5 (mutation testing): readiness signal — is the suite stable enough for Stryker.NET runs?
      (g) **Carry-forward items**: anything that was intentionally NOT done (e.g., NFR-08 anti-parallelism guard worked but cost X hours of synchronization; consider for future projects).
    </step>
    <step order="4">Update `projects/sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair/README.md`: change the status header from "Planning" or "In Progress" to "Complete (closed YYYY-MM-DD)". Add a closure note: "Outcomes A-D delivered: zero-failure baseline; CI gate operational; anti-drift governance shipped. See `ledgers/exit-ledger.md` for evidence + `notes/lessons-learned.md` for retrospective."</step>
    <step order="5">Invoke `/repo-cleanup` skill (per the skill SKILL.md instructions). The skill validates structure compliance and removes ephemeral files. Capture its output — any deletions/cleanups go in the commit summary.</step>
    <step order="6">Update `projects/sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair/current-task.md`:
      - "Phase: ✅ Complete — project closed YYYY-MM-DD"
      - "Last Updated: YYYY-MM-DD by task 090 (wrap-up)"
      - "Current Task: none — project closed"
      - "Next Action: none — see `notes/lessons-learned.md` for follow-on Project 2-5 guidance"
    </step>
    <step order="7">Update `projects/sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`: mark task 090 as ✅. Confirm all other tasks (001-086) are also ✅.</step>
    <step order="8">Verify `git status` shows only files in `projects/sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair/` modified (or any cleanup artifacts from `/repo-cleanup`).</step>
    <step order="9">Final commit: "chore: close sdap-bff.api-test-suite-repair project". Push to remote per `push-to-github` skill. Do NOT merge to master from this task — merge is a separate owner-driven decision per project convention.</step>
  </steps>

